--------------------------------------------------------------------------
CODING IN GENERAL
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
What you code and how you code here at DarkWind are very important.
First and formost is theme, as stated in multiple places, the theme
of DarkWind has a fairly serious tone as well as being medieval in
nature.  With the opening of New Domains, this is changing slightly,
but the rule still applies.  You are required to code within the
the theme of each domain and all domains are to have a fairly serious
tone to them.  Areas such as Cartoon land, Cybertech, Silly land,
Futuristic, etc will 100% not be allowed or tolorated period, so don't
even bother to mention or ask about it.
 
Values of objects are also an important topic.  As far as weapons and
armours go, you should ALWAYS set_value(-1) on these objects and let
them be autovalued.  If an object has some sort of unique property that
doesnt get reflected in the autovalue, you can set_value(-1,<amount>)
where amount is the amount to be added to the autovalue.  Its always
great to make that neat object that is worth a fortune, but as a wizard
you must always keep in mind game balance.  If too much money is put
into the game, the economy of the game will get thrown out of whack.
 
as far as rooms go, we no longer will approve rooms with 1 or 2 line 
descs, nor will we approve rooms that don't have add_looks for every
thing described in the rooms long or in other add_looks.
 
Also, in general, if you feel the need to give a monster something
of value, please give them an object of value over straight cash.  How
often do you think monsters walk around with a fortune in cash on them.
It is much more likely that a monster would carry around his favorite
sword worth X money while on guard than it is that the guard would be
carryig around a backpack full of X coins.
 
Remember this simple rule when coding: "Quality is better than quantity".
Anybody can code 200 boring rooms with random monsters or treasure.
We want areas that are interesting as well as rewarding.
 
There will also be some policies going into place soon on minimum
coding requirements to become or stay a wizard.  We do not really want
wizards that are not even remotly productive.  Part of being a wizard
is learning to code and opening up an area.  If a person doesn't feel
up to this then they would probobly do better as a player.  If a person
wants to stay a wizard but doesn't feel upto opening and area, we can
find you a project to work on in its place (we have plenty).
 
